    description: "Jog Falls is the second-highest plunge waterfall in India, where the Sharavathi River drops 253 meters in four distinct cascades—Raja, Rani, Rover, and Rocket—through the lush Western Ghats of Karnataka. The falls are most spectacular during and after the monsoon season when the river runs full.",
    history: "The Linganamakki Dam built upstream in 1948 reduced the natural flow of the falls significantly outside of monsoon season. The falls were first described by British surveyors in the colonial era. They were featured on the Indian 100-rupee note in 1997. A power station at the base generates electricity for the surrounding region.",
