    category: "Waterfall",
    description: "Dudhsagar, meaning 'sea of milk' in Konkani, is a four-tiered waterfall on the Mandovi River at the Goa-Karnataka border, where white foamy water cascades 310 meters down a steep cliff face through dense evergreen forest. The Konkan Railway bridge spanning the gorge adds a dramatic human element to the natural spectacle.",
    history: "Dudhsagar is one of India's tallest waterfalls and is located within Bhagwan Mahavir Wildlife Sanctuary and Mollem National Park. The railway line passing through the gorge was built by the Portuguese in 1916 when Goa was under colonial rule. Access to the falls was restricted after tourists drowned, and a trekking permit system was introduced in 2021.",
    imageUrl: "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Dudhsagar_Falls_Goa.jpg/800px-Dudhsagar_Falls_Goa.jpg"
